===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|knight|lang=enm}}, {{term|kniht|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|cniht|lang=ang}}, {{term|cneht|lang=ang}}, {{term|cneoht||boy, youth, servant, attendant, retainer, disciple, warrior, boyhood, junior member of a guild|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*knehtaz}} (compare Dutch {{term|knecht||attendant, servant|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Knecht||lad, slave|lang=de}}), originally ‘billet (wood), block of wood’ (compare Dutch {{term|laarzeknecht||boot-jack|lang=nl}}, dialectal German {{term|Knüchtel||bat, club|lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*gnegʰ-}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*gen-}} ‘to ball up, pinch, compress’.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[warrior]], especially of the [[Middle Ages]].
#: ''King Arthur and the '''Knights''' of the Round Table''
# A young servant or follower; a military attendant.
# Nowadays, a person on whom a [[knighthood]] has been conferred by a [[monarch]].
# {{context|chess|lang=en}} A [[chess piece]], often in the shape of a [[horse]]'s head, that is moved two squares in one direction and one at right angles to that direction in a single move, leaping over any intervening pieces.
# {{context|card games|dated|lang=en}} A playing card bearing the figure of a knight; the knave or jack.

